<HL>
   New Securities Issues
</HL>
<DATE>
05/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19
</SO>
<CO>
   MO FNM Z.CSU J.NOM FRE
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
</IN>
<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                         CORPORATE
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Philip Morris Cos. -- $150 million of senior notes, due
Aug. 15, 1991, were priced at par to yield 9%. The
non-callable notes were priced at a spread of 53 basis points
above the bond equivalent yield of the Treasury's one-year
bill. Rated single-A-3 by Moody's Investors Service Inc. and
Single-A by Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., the issue will be sold
through underwriters led by Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
                                                                                                       

                         MUNICIPALS
                                                                                                       

   Minneapolis, Minn., Housing Redevelopment Authority $159.4
million of health care system revenue bonds were tentatively
priced by a Goldman Sachs &amp; Co. group. The issue, for the
city of St. Paul, consists of Series 1990 A, Series 1990 B,
and Series 1990 C. The $100 million Series A bonds comprise
serial bonds that were priced to yield from 6.30% in 1991 to
7.375% in 2002. Term bonds due in 2005 were priced with a
7.40% coupon at 99.085 to yield 7.50%; term bonds due in 2014
were priced with a 7.40% coupon at 98 to yield 7.58%. The
Series A bonds, MBIA-insured, have a triple-A rating from
both Moody's and S&amp;P. The $38 million Series B bonds comprise
serial bonds that yield from 6.60% in 1991 to 7.60% in 2001.
Term bonds due in 2014 were priced with an 8% coupon to yield
8.15%. The Series B bonds are rated single-A by Moody's and
single-A-minus by S&amp;P. As for the $21.4 million Series C
bonds, they comprise serial bonds that were priced to yield
from 7.00% in 1995 to 7.60% in 2001. Term bonds due in 2019
were priced with a 8% coupon to yield 8.15%. The Series C
bonds are rated single-A by Moody's and single-A-Minus by
S&amp;P.
   Central Arizona Water Conservation District -- $152.5
million of revenue bonds were tentatively priced by a John
Nuveen &amp; Co. group. The Series 1990 A issue, for the Central
Arizona Project contract, was priced to yield from 6.60% in
1994 to 7.624% on term bonds due in 2010. Zero-coupon capital
appreciation bonds were priced to yield 7.25% at maturity in
2008. The issue has been rated single-A-1 by Moody's and
double-A-minus by S&amp;P.
   Chicago, Ill. -- $75 million of gas supply revenue bonds
were tentatively priced by a Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
group. The issue, for Peoples Gas Light &amp; Coke Co., 1990
Series A, is subject to the alternative minimum tax. The
bonds, due May 1, 2020, carry 8.10% coupons and were priced
at par. A rating of double-A-3 is expected from Moody's and
double-A-minus from S&amp;P.
   Maryland Health and Higher Education Facilities Authority
-- $68.6 million of revenue bonds were tentatively priced by
a Goldman Sachs &amp; Co. group. The bonds, for Sinai Hospital of
Baltimore, were priced to yield from 6.10% in 1991 to 7.53%
in 2019. The AMBAC-insured issue has triple-A ratings from
both Moody's and S&amp;P.
                                                                                                       

                         MORTGAGES
                                                                                                       

   Federal National Mortgage Association -- $750.1 million of
real estate mortgage investment conduit securities were
offered in 23 classes by Bear Stearns &amp; Co. The offering,
series 1990-60, is backed by Fannie Mae's 9 1/2% securities.
There were no immediate details from Bear Stearns.
   First Boston Corp. -- $500 million of real estate mortgage
investment conduit securities were offered through its
Collateralized Mortgage Securities Corp. unit. The issue,
CMSC 1990-3, is backed by Government National Mortgage
Assocation's 9 1/2% securities. No other information on the
issue was immediately available from First Boston.
   Nomura Mortgage Capital Corp. -- $400 million of real
estate mortgage investment conduit securities were offered in
14 classes by Nomura Securities International Inc. The
offering, Series 1990-1, and backed by Ginnie Mae's 10%
securities, has been structured to yield from 9 1/2% to 10%.
   Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. -- $300 million of real
estate mortgage investment conduit securities were offered in
14 classes through Citibank. The offering, Freddie Mac's
series 170, and backed by Freddie Mac's 10% securities, was
structured to yield from 8% to 10%.
   Federal National Mortgage Association -- $300 million of
real estate mortgage investment conduit securities were
offered in 15 classes by First Boston Corp. The offering,
Series 1990-61, is backed by Fannie Mae's 10% securities. No
details were available.
</TEXT>
