<HL>
   Technology and Health:
   Irradiating Poultry
   To Curb Bacteria
   Approved by FDA
   ----
   By Bruce Ingersoll
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   RTII
</CO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)
</IN>
<GV>
FOOD AND DRUG ADMINISTRATION (FDA)
AGRICULTURE DEPARTMENT (AGD)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Food and Drug Administration approved
the use of irradiation to control salmonella and other
bacteria in poultry believed partly to blame for rising rates
of food-borne illness.
   FDA scientists described irradiation as a safe and
effective process for, in effect, pasteurizing solid foods.
As in the heat-pasteurization of milk, they said, zapping
poultry with X-rays, gamma radiation or electron radiation
greatly reduces, but doesn't eliminate, all bacteria. Thus,
although irradiated poultry would be safe longer than
untreated poultry, it would still require refrigeration, just
as pasteurized milk does.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Despite FDA assurances that irradiation doesn't make food
radioactive or expose consumers to radiation, the poultry
industry expects consumer resistance to be a problem.
   "It would be fair to say at this time that you won't see
companies jumping to take advantage of this technology, not
unless they feel the consumer will buy the product," said
Stephen Pretanik, science director for the National Broiler
Council, a trade group for major chicken processors. "There's
an element out there that is going to fight this."
   Mr. Pretanik said that a consumer-education effort by
government and industry is needed to overcome "a lot of
misunderstanding and misinformation" about irradiation. Roger
Coleman, spokesman for the National Food Processors
Association, added, "The issue is consumer acceptance."
   FDA approval had been sought by the Agriculture
Department, which is responsible for inspecting meat and
poultry products, and by RTI Inc., a Rockaway, N.J., company
engaged in food irradiation. "This will allow industry a
chance to use this new technology if it chooses to," said
James Greene, a department spokesman.
   The department is particularly concerned about such
food-borne pathogens as salmonella and campylobacter, major
causes of illnesses. Poultry accounted for almost 10% of the
illnesses in U.S. outbreaks that were traced to a food source
between 1973 and 1987. FDA scientists estimate that almost
every American becomes sick from eating tainted food once
every year or so. The illnesses range from a stomachache to
an incapacitating, and sometimes fatal, attack.
   The FDA already has authorized limited uses of irradiation
to inhibit sprouting in potatoes, retard spoilage in produce,
and control insects in herbs, spices, grains and other foods.
   The latest approval was based in part on studies in which
lab animals were put on diets containing irradiated poultry.
Irradiation at the relatively low levels approved reduces the
number of pathogenic and spoilage bacteria but doesn't
sterilize the poultry, FDA officials said. As a result,
poultry products would continue to require proper handling
and refrigeration by retailers and consumers to prevent
surviving organisms from multiplying.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900502-0144
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900502-0144.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Bush Again Expresses Concern Over Cost
   Of S&amp;L Bailout; New FDIC Head Sought
   ----
   By Gerald F. Seib
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The White House again expressed concern
about the rising cost of the savings-and-loan bailout and
said it is beginning the process of picking a new leader of
the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. to handle it.
   "We certainly are concerned about additional costs, and it
seems clear there will be higher costs than originally
estimated," said White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater. "We
don't have agreement on how much they will be."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The White House voiced similar concerns several weeks ago,
after Congress's General Accounting Office estimated that the
bailout's cost would be significantly higher than originally
estimated. Subsequently, President Bush met FDIC Chairman
William Seidman to discuss the price tag for the bailout. Mr.
Seidman also met privately last week with White House Chief
of Staff John Sununu, Bush administration aides said.
   Mr. Seidman has said he intends to leave his FDIC post
before his term expires next year, and Mr. Fitzwater
suggested that Mr. Bush hasn't tried to stop him from
leaving. The spokesman said that while a firm departure date
hasn't been set, the White House has begun internal
discussions about a successor for Mr. Seidman. Other
officials said it's likely to be several weeks before a firm
list of candidates is completed.
   Under last year's huge thrift-industry restructuring law,
the FDIC was given authority over the thrift
deposit-insurance fund and the Resolution Trust Corp., which
was created to merge and sell insolvent S&amp;Ls.
   Mr. Seidman has irritated Bush administration officials
with his outspoken assertions that the S&amp;L bailout probably
would be far more costly than the administration's official
estimate of $166 billion over 10 years. The FDIC chairman's
style has earned him plaudits among Democrats, though, and
some of them yesterday urged President Bush to ask him to
stay.
   Administration aides say the White House has begun
increasing its "focus" on the festering problem of failing
thrifts. White House aides largely delegated the matter to
the Treasury Department after the Bush administration
completed the S&amp;L legislation last August.
   Since then, though, it's become clear that the
administration's cost estimates for the bailout weren't
realistic. Last month, the GAO, Congress's investigative arm,
said the 10-year cost of the bailout likely will be roughly
$243 billion, not $166 billion as the administration
initially suggested. The GAO also said the cost over 30 years
should reach $325 billion, rather than the $257 billion that
the agency itself once estimated.
   White House officials say they don't have the time or
staff to oversee the thrift bailout, but they seem resigned
to devoting more attention to the problem in the next few
months.
   Mr. Seidman has said many times that he won't stay for his
entire term, and Mr. Fitzwater said the White House will be
looking for "new leadership there that will carry out an
aggressive program" when the chairman leaves.
   Mr. Seidman hasn't said precisely when he will be going,
but it seems that he will want to stay through the end of
June. By that time, the Resolution Trust Corp. hopes to have
sold 141 more ailing S&amp;Ls, which would represent a big
acceleration. Only about 60 have been sold so far.
   Separately, Sen. Howard Metzenbaum (D., Ohio) urged Mr.
Seidman to renegotiate some government-backed S&amp;L sales that
occurred nearly two years ago. Sen. Metzenbaum said that a
recently discovered memo indicates it would have been cheaper
to liquidate a group of five Texas thrifts, rather than sell
them to New York financier Ronald Perelman.
   In a February 1989 memorandum to the president of the Home
Loan Bank of Dallas, a lower-level regulator contended that
regulators overstated the cost of liquidation by $1.8 billion
at the time the deal was made in December 1988. "In my
opinion the {agency} has grossly overstated the liquidation
cost estimate," said the memo from regulatory analyst Jeff
Potter.
   The transaction has emerged as the most controversial of
nearly 100 government thrift sales struck in 1988. It
included about $5 billion in assistance to a newly created
thrift, First Gibraltar Bank, over 10 years, as well as
nearly $1 billion more in tax breaks for Mr. Perelman's
holding company, MacAndrews &amp; Forbes Inc. Renegotiating the
deal could involve such things as paying off high-interest
government notes, to reduce the cost to taxpayers.
   ---
   Paulette Thomas contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
