<HL>
   Tuesday's Markets:
   Stocks Gain
   Due to Data
   On Growth
   ---
   Purchasers' Report
   Pushes Bonds Lower;
   Dollar Closes Mixed
   ----
   By Douglas R. Sease
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   Evidence of increasingly robust economic growth gave stock
prices a little boost while pushing bond prices lower.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 12.16 points to
2668.92 in moderate trading. Long-term bond prices slipped
about 3/8 point, or about $3.75 for each $1,000 of face
amount, while the dollar was mixed. The big May Day holiday
in Europe curtailed trading action in both the bond and
currency markets.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Investors were caught by surprise when the National
Association of Purchasing Management reported that its index
of economic activity for April jumped to 50.2% from 48.9% in
March. Economists had expected only a tiny increase in the
measure of the nation's industrial economy. If the index is
below 50% the economy is presumed to be contracting, while
readings above 50% show an expanding economy. The April
level, the highest in a year, tends to support a view that
the economy and inflation are both picking up steam.
   The immediate effect of the purchasing manager's report
was a modest retreat in bond prices, which had risen slightly
in early New York trading. Bond investors have been shaken in
recent weeks by the mounting evidence that inflation is
accelerating. Accelerating inflation is expected to force the
Federal Reserve to boost short-term interest rates sometime
soon and the purchasing managers' report will, if anything,
advance the Fed's timetable.
   While they await a Fed move, bond traders are braced, too,
for today's Treasury announcement about next week's big
quarterly refunding auction. They worry that Japanese
investors won't be aggressive buyers since interest rates in
Japan are competitive with rates available here. If Japanese
investors shun the auction, yields on the Treasury issues
will have to rise to attract other buyers.
   But if rising economic activity worries bond investors, it
leaves stock investors in a quandary. On the plus side, a
more robust economy could spur corporate earnings to higher
levels later this year. But the higher interest rates that
usually accompany rising inflation increase the cost of doing
business. And if the Federal Reserve really cracks down and
pushes short-term rates sharply higher to curb inflation, the
economy could slip into a recession.
   Right now investors are taking a positive view, noting
that International Business Machine Chairman John Akers on
Monday predicted a "substantially improved" performance this
year.
   In major market action:
                                                                                                       

   Stock prices rose. Volume on the New York Stock Exchange
totaled 149 million shares. Advancing issues on the Big Board
were ahead of decliners 820 to 679.
                                                                                                       

   Bond prices were lower. The Treasury's benchmark 30-year
issue lost 3/8 point, or $3.75 for each $1,000 of face
amount. The yield on the issue rose to 9.03%.
                                                                                                       

   The dollar barely budged. In late New York trading the
currency was quoted at 1.6808 marks and 158.83 yen compared
with 1.6796 marks and 158.90 yen Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900502-0100
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900502-0100.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Rule of Law:
   Milken's Tragedy: Oh How the Mighty Fall Before RICO
   ----
   By L. Gordon Crovitz
</HL>
<DATE>
05/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A17
</SO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
</GV>
<LP>
   Melodramas have their place even in law, but so far the
atmospherics have obscured the Michael Milken tragedy. The
shadows will some day recede. Do not be surprised if the
Greek chorus then moans a deeper loss than the personal
anguish of Mr. Milken. A legal system that could declare
itself satisfied with last week's plea bargain is a system
headed for a fall.
   Proportionality and fairness crumpled to give way to the
prosecution of Mr. Milken: The prosecutorial tactics were a
cannon to the flea of the six eventual pleas by Mr. Milken.
His plea has little to do with the original indictment's
allegations. The liquidation of Drexel Burnham Lambert and
Mr. Milken's $600 million fine completely dwarf the harm done
to clients and investors, which likely comes to less than $1
million. Without minimizing his offenses, the Justice
Department and Securities and Exchange Commission have some
explaining to do.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Milken has settled for some jail time and a possibly
partly tax-deductible fine. What remains unclear is how great
a criminal we should view Mr. Milken or how proud we should
be of our legal system for winning this plea bargain.
   Let's first understand what Mr. Milken did not admit. The
indictment was 98 charges of racketeering, insider trading
and a manipulation scam underlying the junk-bond and takeover
markets.
   No one seems to have noticed that Mr. Milken did not admit
to any of the charges as originally described in the
indictment. Instead, prosecutors indicted first, asked
questions later. As Justice Robert Jackson warns nearby, few
things are as dangerous as a prosecutor who finds a target,
then looks for crimes to pin on him.
   It was no surprise that Mr. Milken did not admit to any
RICO counts -- these were included solely as rubber hoses to
bludgeon a plea. But Mr. Milken also did not admit to any
insider trading. In other words, those who consider him a
common crook must also think he is an idiot. At the peak of
the takeover battles, Mr. Milken had huge amounts of inside
information, probably more inside information than everyone
else in the market combined. Prosecutors apparently didn't
find a single case of misusing this information.
   Most important, this means Mr. Milken is no Ivan Boesky, a
real crook who made easy money by trading suitcases of cash
for stolen inside information. So why did prosecutors agree
to give Mr. Boesky a reduced sentence for fingering Mr.
Milken? Maybe they assumed there was more to the Milken case
than exists. After all, former prosecutor Rudolph Giuliani
also leaped to wrong conclusions in the aborted
insider-trading indictment of investment bankers Robert
Freeman, Richard Wigton and Timothy Tabor.
   Of the six crimes to which Mr. Milken pleaded, only three
were in the indictment in even a distorted form. The
Fischbach takeover, for example, is better viewed as Mr.
Boesky leaning on Mr. Milken for a favor than the other way
around. The indictment didn't mention the one crime where Mr.
Milken harmed clients. This was a commission-shaving scheme
that cost clients several hundred thousand dollars -- though
legally if only disclosed.
   His lawyers noted that most of Mr. Milken's crimes were
accommodating the more serious offenses of others. Mr. Milken
said he knew at the time that his acts were wrong, but didn't
say he knew that they were crimes. Until recent years no one
could have imagined that victimless offenses such as aiding
and abetting someone else in filing a false net capital Form
X-17A-5 or an incomplete disclosure 13-D Form would warrant
more than a harsh letter from the SEC or a nominal fine.
   If prosecutors were so sure of their case, why the
extraordinary pressure on Mr. Milken to cop a plea? RICO
makes a farce of the entire case. The Justice Department's
own prosecutorial guidelines prohibit such "imaginative
prosecutions" under the anti-mobster law because of RICO's
brutal force.
   RICO meant Mr. Milken faced a possible jail sentence of
520 years and a fine of $11 billion. We lack the finality of
a trial partly because the Princeton/Newport trial put Mr.
Milken on notice that vague RICO allegations of fraud are
enough for convictions. Prosecutors made his lawyer brother
an indicted co-racketeer even though he had little to do with
the allegedly illegal transactions. Settling freed the
brother as a RICO hostage.
   It's also possible that some prosecutors actually equate
investment banking and racketeering. One lawyer recounts the
chilling response he got when he tried to persuade top
Justice officials that RICO was inappropriate in a securities
case. A Justice official asked, "Isn't putting a company in
play criminal and an act of racketeering?" It explains a lot
if prosecutors think hostile takeovers are crimes.
   I also understand that to get the plea prosecutors
threatened new indictments in every state where a savings and
loan bought bonds from Drexel. Trying to smear Mr. Milken
with the thrift mess would have been high irony; until
Congress forced fire sales, junk bonds were among thrifts'
safer investments. Mr. Milken must have wondered what next?
when an FBI agent was dispatched to interrogate his
92-year-old grandfather.
   After all this, Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said this
shows the government won't abide "crime in the suites." SEC
Chairman Richard Breeden held a press conference to say that
Mr. Milken's "admissions today demonstrate that he stood at
the center of a network of manipulation, fraud and deceit."
   What this case in fact shows is that if prosecutors had
the courage of Mr. Milken's supposed convictions, they should
have dropped the abusive RICO counts and gone to court. Now
prosecutors will use their sentencing memorandum to the judge
to retry the case without risk of rebuttal.
   Mr. Milken's great accomplishments do not excuse cutting
legal corners, but justice requires viewing Mr. Milken by all
that he did with his financial genius. His hubris was that
getting the deals done came to be more important than
remembering that even in the most advanced societies
renegades get no margin for error. In the end, prosecutorial
abuses yield the best perspective on the Milken plea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900502-0099
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900502-0099.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Emerson Electric
   Enters Guilty Plea
   In Pentagon Case
   ----
   By Robert L. Rose
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<CO>
   EMR
</CO>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   Emerson Electric Co. pleaded guilty in federal court in
St. Louis to inflating cost proposals on certain military
contracts, and agreed to pay $14 million as part of a
settlement with the government.
   The agreement stems from allegations by the government
that at least from Jan. 1, 1983, to Sept. 30, 1987, Emerson's
Electronics and Space division submitted "false and inflated"
cost and price figures on contracts on which it was the only
supplier.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Specifically, Emerson pleaded guilty to four counts of
making false statements on government contracts for equipment
used to test instruments on military aircraft. In addition to
the $14 million civil settlement, which goes to the Defense
Department, the company agreed to pay fines totaling $40,000.
   The settlement closes a two-year grand jury investigation
of the St. Louis maker of electric and electronic products.
The investigation became public in February 1988 when a team
of Defense Department investigators made a surprise search of
the division's Ferguson, Mo., plant.
   Investigators were trying to determine whether the company
illegally switched military vehicle parts from a U.S. program
to vehicles sold to Egypt.
   U.S. Attorney Thomas E. Dittmeier, whose office led the
investigation, said in an interview the search led to
evidence of the cost overestimates. He also said his office
found "possible criminal violations" in Emerson's parts
transfer practices, but said it allowed the company to plea
only to the cost charges as part of the agreement.
   Joe Adorjan, Emerson vice chairman, denied in an interview
any wrongdoing by the company in the parts transfer area. But
he called the guilty plea on the cost charges "a serious
event for us."
   Emerson said it negotiated the civil settlement to
"resolve a number of open issues" with the Defense
Department. It also said in a statement that the agreement
"is in the best economic interest of shareholders." It said
it included the settlement in its second-quarter results
announced yesterday, in which it said profit rose nearly 6%
to $156.2 million, or 70 cents a share. Sales rose nearly 6%
to $1.91 billion.
   While it's not about to interrupt Emerson's 32-year string
of higher earnings, the plea agreement further tarnishes the
company's reputation in the defense business. The Defense
Department could still bar the company from contracts, but
Mr. Adjoran said in the interview that the company is
"optimistic" that won't happen.
   Both Emerson Electric and the U.S. attorney said the
company corrected the cost-estimating systems before the
government investigation began, and that Emerson cooperated
in the investigation.
   Early last year, the Navy suspended Emerson's Hazeltine
unit from competing for and receiving new government
contracts. The three-month suspension came after Hazeltine
pleaded guilty to conspiracy and other charges in the
Pentagon procurement scandal.
   In March 1989, a former Hazeltine executive was sentenced
to three months in jail after admitting that he conspired to
obtain inside information about competitors' bids on a
contract.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
