<HL>
   Savings-Bond Interest Rate
   Is Raised for Next 6 Months
</HL>
<DATE>
05/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. savings bonds will earn interest
at a 7.01% rate from May 1 through Oct. 31, up slightly from
6.98% during the previous six months, the Treasury Department
said.
   Treasurer Catalina Villalpando said the new rate "will
keep savings bonds in the competitive range with other
market-sensitive instruments during the coming months."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Savings-bond interest rates are changed each May 1 and
Nov. 1 to reflect open-market rates. They are based on 85% of
the yield from five-year Treasury securities, which have
averaged 8.25%.
   Bonds must be held at least five years to earn
market-based rates. However, holders of savings bonds are
guaranteed a minimum rate, which currently is 6%.
</TEXT>
