<HL>
   Ex-Day-Care Operator
   Pleads Guilty to Fraud
   In Communications
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   T ITT WU
</CO>
<IN>
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   CHICAGO -- A former day-care center operator pleaded
guilty in U.S. District Court here to defrauding
telecommunications companies out of nearly $600,000 as the
head of a nationwide computer-hacking ring.
   Leslie Lynne Doucette, 36 years old, working with 152
alleged co-schemers, fraudulently obtained 481 telephone
credit-card codes, according to the plea agreement, and then
published them in voice-mail systems that were accessed by
other hackers. The scheme was discovered when a suburban
Chicago real-estate brokerage complained that its voice-mail
system had been invaded by the hackers, who had changed the
system's passwords.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors charged Ms. Doucette last year in the
scheme, which according to the indictment resulted in a loss
of $1.6 million of telephone and computer services from the
communications concerns, including American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph Co., ITT Corp., and Western Union Corp.
   The one count to which Ms. Doucette eventually pleaded
guilty carries a maximum sentence of ten years in prison, and
a $1 million fine.
</TEXT>
