<HL>
   Business Brief -- Occidental Petroleum Corp.:
   Two Units Ordered to Pay
   $28 Million to Coastal Unit
</HL>
<DATE>
05/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   OXY CGP
</CO>
<LP>
   A federal court in Cheyenne, Wyo., ordered two units of
Occidental Petroleum Corp., Los Angeles, to pay $28 million
to Colorado Interstate Gas Co. for wrongful interference in a
contractual relationship between Colorado Interstate and a
gas supplier.
   The judgment was recently disclosed by Occidental in a
regulatory filing. Occidental also said it has appealed the
judgment to the 10th Circuit Court in Denver.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The litigation began in 1984 when Colorado Interstate, a
unit of Houston-based Coastal Corp., sued Natural Gas
Pipeline Co. of America and NGPL-Trailblazer Inc. for alleged
antitrust violations, breach of contract and wrongful
interference.
   Last September, the 10th Circuit Court overturned a lower
court ruling that ordered the Occidental units to pay $412
million to Colorado Interstate on the antitrust and
breach-of-contract charges. But the circuit court upheld
Colorado Interstate's wrongful interference claim. The two
sides disputed the amount of the claim.
   The Wyoming ruling affirmed Colorado Interstate's claim
that the judgment was for $28 million, including interest.
Occidental maintained that the amount should be only $8
million. Separately, a Coastal spokesman said Colorado
Interstate petitioned the U.S. Supreme Court last week to
review the circuit court's ruling on the antitrust and breach
of contract allegations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
