<DOCNO>
WSJ900502-0022
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900502-0022.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Amex Seeks to List
   U.S. Stock-Index
   3-Year Warrants
   ----
   By George Anders
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C21
</SO>
<CO>
   SB MS BT PWJ
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- The American Stock Exchange wants to list U.S.
stock-index warrants that would let investors bet on the
market's direction over the next three years.
   Long-term warrants are the closest thing to a popular new
product on Wall Street these days. In particular, put
warrants on Japan's Nikkei 225-stock index have attracted
wide trading interest among U.S. individuals and
institutions. Put warrants rise in value when an index
declines, and holders of Nikkei put warrants profited
handsomely on the Japanese stock market's recent plunge.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   So far, the only stock-index warrants traded in the U.S.
have been based on Japanese or British indexes. But subject
to Securities and Exchange Commission approval, the Amex
wants to start trading three-year warrants based on the
20-stock Major Market Index.
   The new Amex warrants would be underwritten by a Wall
Street firm or commercial bank. Amex Chairman James Jones
says Salomon Brothers Inc., Goldman Sachs &amp; Co., Morgan
Stanley &amp; Co., Bankers Trust Co. and PaineWebber Inc. have
all shown interest in rolling out the new warrants.
   Market professionals said the Amex may find some interest
in its warrants, but they added that it is entering a crowded
field. The Nikkei warrants achieved much of their popularity
because it was difficult for most U.S. investors to find any
other way of betting on a Japanese market decline.
   With the U.S. stock market, however, investors already
have several ways to bet long term on the market's direction.
Most Wall Street firms already make an over-the-counter
market in long-maturity stock-index warrants and options.
   In addition, most professional traders find they can
easily simulate a long-term warrant by trading in the
stock-index futures market and "rolling" their positions into
later-maturity contracts as existing contracts near their
expiration dates. And a two-year option on Standard &amp; Poor's
500-Stock Index, traded in the Chicago commodities markets,
has attracted little interest to date.
   Nonetheless, Amex officials seem willing to take their
chances. "Traditionally, the Amex has tried to be more
flexible and innovative about its new products," says Amex
President Ken Liebler. "Some of them are hits, and some
aren't. If they aren't hits, we move on."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900502-0021
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900502-0021.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Hill &amp; Knowlton Stirs Ire
   Over Its Work for Turkey
</HL>
<DATE>
05/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Hill &amp; Knowlton, whose Washington office
last month disclosed plans to wage an anti-abortion campaign
on behalf of the nation's Roman Catholic bishops, is
generating new controversy over another client: the
government of Turkey.
   In a letter to Hill &amp; Knowlton Chairman Robert Gray,
Armenian Assembly of America accused the New York-based
public relations firm of seeking to "censor" U.S. schoolbooks
regarding the 1915 mass deaths of Christian Armenians in
Turkey. Armenian Assembly labels the 1915 events as genocide.
Estimates of those killed range from several hundred thousand
to more than one million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Under an agreement signed last June by representatives of
Hill &amp; Knowlton and the Turkish embassy, the firm agreed to
help "rectify substantial factual errors about contemporary
Turkey and Turkish history contained in secondary-school
social science textbooks."
   Tacan Ilam, press consulate for the Turkish embassy, said
Hill &amp; Knowlton wasn't asked to promote any particular
interpretation of the 1915 events in U.S. schoolbooks. He
said the Turkish embassy was responding to a number of
factual errors about Turkey in U.S. textbooks, none of them
involving the Armenian deaths. Hill &amp; Knowlton hasn't yet
recommended specific changes in textbook language, according
to its senior vice president, Chuck Pucie, but he added that
"is not to say we would not do so."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900502-0020
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900502-0020.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   BCCI Discloses Net Loss
   Of $498 Million for 1989
</HL>
<DATE>
05/02/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A13
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- Bank of Credit &amp; Commerce International said it
had a net loss of $498 million in 1989, largely as a result
of $600 million in loan charges.
   The closely held bank, which had a net loss of $48 million
in 1988 after loan provisions totaling $145 million, also
confirmed that the Abu Dhabi government injected $400 million
to help it meet international loan standards. The injection,
which included the issue of new shares in the bank, boosted
Abu Dhabi's stake to 77%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Earlier this week, it was reported that Abu Dhabi had
become the majority holder of BCCI by acquiring a 20% stake
held by Saudi Arabia's Bin-Mahfouz family. Even before the
acquisition and cash injection, the emirate and its ruling
family members represented the largest block of shareholders
in the bank, which is based in Luxembourg.
   BCCI said it had operating profit before loan provisions
of $224 million, up from $192 million in 1988. It added that
total capital after the cash injection was $1.48 billion, up
from $1.42 billion at the end of 1988. Total assets were
$23.5 billion, up from $20.6 billion.
   BCCI didn't disclose full 1989 operating results. Its
brief statement followed reports that it would announce sharp
losses for the year and possibly sweeping organizational
changes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
